    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>As the day progresses as a consequence of the rain there will be only a slight increase in the danger of moist and wet avalanches.</highlights>
      <comment>At low and intermediate altitudes and at low and intermediate altitudes individual moist and wet avalanches are possible as a consequence of the rain. &lt;br/> Below approximately 2600 m moist avalanches can penetrate even deep layers and reach quite a large size. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Especially steep shady slopes high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers in the old snowpack can be released especially by large additional loads. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> There is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. This applies especially in particular at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>The weather conditions fostered a gradual strengthening of the snowpack. Towards its surface, the snowpack is largely stable and its surface has a melt-freeze crust that is strong in many cases. &lt;br/> Especially steep shady slopes high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers exist in the snowpack. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/> In places that are protected from the wind in all altitude zones a lot of snow is lying for the time of year. &lt;br/> The rain will give rise as the day progresses to increasing moistening of the snowpack at low and intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/></comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
